---
title: Keep entire checkpoints out of Vercel deployments
publishedAt: "2026-05-31"
---

When a GitHub repository is connected to Vercel, every push can become a Preview Deployment.

Most of the time, that is exactly what I want. A pull request gets a URL, checks show up next to CI, and the repository naturally becomes connected to a place where I can inspect the change.

But I recently ran into a small bit of noise.

In a project using `entire.io`, the branch `entire/checkpoints/v1` is pushed automatically. That branch exists for entire's checkpoints. It is useful state for the tool, but it is not an application branch that I want Vercel to deploy.

To Vercel, though, it is still a GitHub branch receiving pushes.

So every checkpoint push can produce another Preview Deployment. Nothing is broken, but the deployment list and GitHub checks start to include deployments that are not connected to the product surface I am trying to review.

The fix is small: tell Vercel that this branch should not be deployed.

### Configure the branch in vercel.json

Vercel supports branch-level deployment control through `git.deploymentEnabled` in `vercel.json`.

For `entire/checkpoints/v1`, the configuration looks like this:

```json
{
  "$schema": "https://openapi.vercel.sh/vercel.json",
  "git": {
    "deploymentEnabled": {
      "entire/checkpoints/v1": false
    }
  }
}
```

If the project already has a `vercel.json`, keep the existing settings and add the `git` block next to them.

```json
{
  "$schema": "https://openapi.vercel.sh/vercel.json",
  "crons": [
    {
      "path": "/api/cron",
      "schedule": "*/5 * * * *"
    }
  ],
  "git": {
    "deploymentEnabled": {
      "entire/checkpoints/v1": false
    }
  }
}
```

After this, pushes to `entire/checkpoints/v1` no longer trigger Vercel deployments. Other branches continue to deploy as usual.

### Prefer this over an ignored build command

Vercel also has Ignored Build Step / `ignoreCommand`, and that can be useful in other situations.

For this case, though, the intent is not "start a build and decide to ignore it." The intent is "this branch is not a deployment branch." Keeping that decision in `git.deploymentEnabled` makes the configuration easier to read later.

This is a tiny setting, but it feels like the kind of boundary that becomes more important as agent tools add their own state to a repository.

Checkpoints, metadata, state files, and tool-owned branches can all be useful. They help work resume and make automation more durable. But not all of that state needs to appear in the human review surface.

The checkpoint should remain a checkpoint. The Vercel deployment list should stay focused on branches that represent the application.

That small distinction keeps the tool useful without letting its internal bookkeeping become everyday deployment noise.

